    "strategic_insights": {
      "key_finding_1": "Strong regional convergence on shared barriers (63.8% mention ≥2 of top-3 barriers) indicates cohesive problem definition across ASEAN. Weak capacity and exclusion from decision-making dominate, suggesting systemic governance and capability gaps rather than just environmental issues.",
      "key_finding_2": "High model adoption (70.2% implement ≥1 model; 52.1% implement ≥2 models) shows practical orientation. Community enterprise dominates (53.2%); bycatch mitigation is underrepresented (3.2%), suggesting capacity gap or lower regional priority.",
      "key_finding_3": "Policy engagement is significant but not universal (63.8% have governance signals; 31.9% show strong engagement). 36.2% have no governance signals, suggesting important community-level practitioners outside formal policy systems.",
      "key_finding_4": "Peer learning is core motivation (66.0% express explicit cross-country engagement interest). Strong correlation with policy engagement suggests policy-engaged leaders recognize value of regional networks.",
      "key_finding_5": "Critical opportunity: 36.2% are 'ready but structurally disconnected' (34 applicants showing isolation + governance + peer learning). These leaders demonstrate capacity and ambition but face structural barriers to visibility and support. Highest-impact intervention target for ASEAN program.",
      "regional_opportunity": "Indonesia (44.4% connectivity gap), Philippines (36.0%), and Malaysia (42.9%) show highest concentrations of ready-but-disconnected leaders. Program should prioritize visibility, funding, and peer-learning facilitation for this group.",
      "capacity_building_need": "Philippines shows lower model adoption (60.0%) and peer-learning demand (52.0%), suggesting potential access, language, or organizational barriers. Targeted outreach and capacity building recommended.",
      "underutilized_models": "Bycatch mitigation (3.2%) and aquaculture improvements (8.5%) are significantly underrepresented. Program should facilitate peer learning and knowledge exchange on these models to increase adoption."
